 Hampton here provides an exploration of education in an era of dramatic social and economic upheaval in rural and urban Mexico. This critical ethnographic case study presents Anay’s experiences in a series of narrative essays addressing the economic, social, and political context of her world. This young Mexican woman leads us through Ciudad Juárez in its most violent years, into women’s experiences in the factories, around family and religious commitments as well as personal illness, and on to her achievement of an education through perseverance and creativity.  afunded by Palomeque de Carillo  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aOffshore assembly industry -- Mexico. 0aOffshore assembly industryzMexico. 0aWomen -- Education -- Mexico. 0aWomen -- Mexico -- Social conditions. 0aWomenxEducationzMexico. 0aWomenzMexicoxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh2 aPalomeque de Carilloefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292744288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292744288/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK